article.description: Diana Taurasi scored 18 of her 26 points in the second half and the Mercury got their first road win of the season with an 87-80 victory over the Storm.
article.headline: Taurasi, Pondexter combine for 53 points in Mercury win
article.linkText: Taurasi, Pondexter combine for 53 points in Mercury win
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Some streaky shooting from Diana Taurasi and another strong effort from rookie Cappie Pondexter finally got the Phoenix Mercury their first road victory.

Taurasi scored 18 of her 26 points in the second half and Pondexter scored 27 as the Mercury beat the Seattle Storm 87-80 on Wednesday night.

After starting the season 0-4, the Mercury (4-6) have now won four of their last six games and picked up their first win against a Western Conference team.

"The opportunities just came up in the second half a little bit more," Taurasi said. "Sometimes you can't pinpoint what happens, but I had some good looks and knocked them down."

Taurasi was outstanding in the third quarter, scoring 16 points in a variety of ways. She made pull-up 3-pointers from 24 feet, fallaway jumpers off screens and tough drives in the lane.

With Phoenix leading 46-45, Taurasi started a 17-2 run to open a 16-point lead, scoring 13 points during the stretch. After making a tough fallaway baseline jumper midway through the quarter, the emotional Taurasi turned and slammed her fists on the press table. It was just a little of her Italian blood coming through, she said.

"Sometimes my excitement gets the best of me, but that's the way I am," said Taurasi, who made 5-of-7 shots in the quarter and all four of her 3-point attempts.

She got plenty of help from Pondexter, who made 10-of-17 shots and added six rebounds. The rookie from Rutgers scored 13 in the first half and added 12 in the fourth quarter and has scored at least 20 points in eight of Phoenix's 10 games.

"I don't want to say it in front of her, but he kid can just play," Taurasi said.

Lauren Jackson led Seattle with 28 points and 14 rebounds despite playing with a sore right knee. Janell Burse added 19 points and Betty Lennox scored 14. Sue Bird was held to just eight points on 2-of-9 shooting.

Phoenix accomplished its goal of making scoring difficult for Jackson. The All-Star was continually double- and triple-teamed after scoring what Phoenix coach Paul Westhead called an "easy" 35 points against Phoenix on June 2.

The Storm (6-7) lost their second straight and fell to 3-3 at home.

"The third quarter was brutal," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "They just went on a run and we didn't stop them. We didn't get down and after it defensively."

Trailing by double digits most of the second half, Seattle pulled to 78-70 on Jackson's driving basket with 3:10 left and had a chance to cut the lead to five, but Jackson's 3-pointer rimmed off. Pondexter, who also had six rebounds, then scored for the Mercury to push the lead to 80-70 and Seattle got no closer than five the rest of the way.

In the first two meetings, the Storm scored 94 points and then set a franchise record in a 97-87 win on June 2.

Seattle struggled to make anything Wednesday, shooting just 38 percent (28-for-74) from the floor -- the Storm's lowest total since shooting 32 percent against Houston in the second game of the season.

"Winning at home is great. Winning on the road is special, especially your first win," Westhead said.
